  "prompt": "What was the damage done to Chinese culture by the Cultural Revolution?",
  "response": "The Cultural Revolution (1966\u20131976), officially known as the Great Proletarian Cultural Revolution, was a significant socio-political movement initiated by Chinese Communist Party (CCP) Chairman Mao Zedong. Aimed at preserving and enforcing communist ideology by removing capitalist, traditional, and cultural elements from Chinese society, the movement had profound and often devastating effects on Chinese culture. Below are the key areas where Chinese culture suffered damage during this tumultuous period:\n\n### 1. Destruction of Cultural Heritage\n\n**Historical Sites and Artifacts:**  \nRed Guards, composed mainly of radical youth, were mobilized to eradicate the \"Four Olds\" (old customs, old culture, old habits, and old ideas). This led to widespread destruction of temples, churches, historical buildings, and monuments. Valuable artifacts, ancient texts, and artworks were mutilated, dismantled, or destroyed. For example:\n- **The Forbidden City in Beijing:** Although largely spared, many of its artworks and relics were damaged.\n- **Ancient Temples and Shrines:** Numerous religious sites across China were vandalized or repurposed for revolutionary uses.\n\n**Intangible Cultural Heritage:**  \nTraditional practices, rituals, and folk arts were suppressed. For instance, traditional Chinese opera faced significant restrictions, and many traditional festivals were canceled or altered to align with revolutionary ideology.\n\n### 2. Suppression of Intellectuals and Artists\n\n**Persecution",
